2022 has been an incredible year for us. A year filled with highs & lows and a lot of learning along the way. 
Every year I pick a word for the year & my word for 2022 was intentional. I wanted every decision that we made to have intention behind it. It’s easy in this business to get side tracked & caught up in what everyone else is doing or letting the fear of missing out take over that sometimes you can lose focus. So this year I intentionally took some things off of my plate to give myself the time & space to dream. To really think about where we want to take our business. To spend time with my kids, to travel & work smarter not harder. To take care of myself, my family & enjoy the beauty around us. To think about how we can be successful without being so blinded by success that we lose sight of what is right in front of us. This year was our biggest year yet & I worked less. Don’t get me wrong, I still worked hard but a lot less than before. I dialed in my passions & let go of perfection. I watched with tears streaming down my face as my oldest son graduated from high school & realized how fast it truly goes. I was blessed to work on some incredible projects that I can’t wait to see come to fruition in the coming year. I got to meet some amazing people & had time to reflect. I pushed myself out of my comfort zone & learned to let go. I learned from my mistakes & counted my blessings. I successfully grew houseplants for the first time ever, which for me is a major accomplishment. LOL!!! We grieved the loss of a beloved pet of 16 years but also gained a few more & a flock of chickens. 
There were definitely ups & downs and some days where I felt pushed to the max but we are so incredibly blessed for this life, our farm & all that another year has given us. We get to do this & we are so grateful to all of you that have supported us along the way. 
We’re dreaming big in 2023 & we can’t wait to have you all see what’s coming next. 
Wishing you all a safe & Happy New Year! ✨

Just a friendly reminder for all you sweet pea lovers out there. I’ve spent a few hours this morning answering emails about seed sowing so I thought I would make a post about it. 
For those of you that are starting your sweet pea seeds or getting ready to start your sweet pea seeds. Please remember sweet peas like it cool & the ideal temperature for germination is 50-55 degrees. Plants do best when they are grown cold, in fact as soon as mine have germinated I stick them right into our unheated greenhouse where they stay until planting time. You want short beefy plants not tall, lean & lanky so make sure they have enough light and give them the right conditions. 
A few things you want to avoid with sweet peas:
* heat mats, they like it cool. 
* bottom watering, seeds will rot if they are kept too wet. 
* seed soaking, believe it or not it is unnecessary to soak your sweet pea seeds. 

Following these simple steps & I promise you will be rewarded with tons of beautiful sweet peas in the season ahead. 😊🌱

To soak or not to soak that is the question…. 
Did you know it’s not necessary to soak your sweet pea seeds before planting? I personally am all about working smarter & not harder so if there is an unnecessary step that I can skip sign me up. Sweet pea seeds have a hard outside shell and the thought behind soaking seeds prior to planting is that it speeds up germination but did you know that soaking your seeds can in fact actually reduce your germination rate & introduce fungus & disease to your plants? I know this can tend to be a hot topic amongst sweet pea growers as some religiously soak their seeds every year so if that method works for you that’s great, but just giving you guys a little tip to make your lives a little bit easier & try just putting them straight into the soil. 😊

8/8: my first deadline for my book. 🤗

This morning I hit send & submitted my first batch of writing to my editor. There have been so many emotions swirling inside me since I started writing. Inner reflections paired with excitement, pride, nervousness, vulnerability, self doubt & at times being honestly truly terrified. When I started my flower journey years ago it honestly never crossed my mind that one day I’d be writing a book but I guess looking back to my days in a cubicle it never crossed my mind that one day I’d be a flower farmer either. It wasn’t until some of my sweet pea school students started asking the question that I ever even considered the possibility. The thought of writing a book pushed me so far out of my comfort zone but at the same time filled my soul with so much excitement at the thought of taking my passion for sweet peas from the garden onto the printed page. This year I’m growing a few less flowers here on the farm to make more room & space for myself to grow in other ways. A quieter season to push & challenge myself so that I can hopefully inspire and reach so many more of you with my love of sweet peas. In my sweet pea patch the tops are still frothy & fresh but under their beautiful canopy are tired vines loaded with seed pods & the promise of next years garden. This also translates to the work that’s going on behind the grid of beautiful photos you see here on IG. I’m grateful for the gift of a slower season for myself & dreaming of a time when the keystrokes of today will be replaced with the pages of tomorrow.

Today has been the perfect fall day for planting.…. 

A few years ago I started growing all of our tulips in crates. It was a game changer for us, no more digging trenches, longer stems & the tulips love it! 

How do I do it? It’s really easy…. 
• Fill the bottom of a bulb crate with 2 inches of soil. 
• Plant your tulip bulbs with the pointy end up & close together like eggs in a carton. I can usually fit about 100 bulbs per crate. 
• Then cover them with soil & wait til spring. 

If you’ve never grown them this way before give it a try & see what you think. One things for certain, it’s going to be a beautiful spring…. 🌷

One of the things that I’m the most excited about in the upcoming year is expanding our dahlia seedling patch. If you’ve never grown dahlias from seed before I highly recommend giving it a try, it’s a blast! 

Even within the same pod, every dahlia seed is a different flower & for me it’s like Christmas waiting for them to bloom to see what they are going to look like. Dahlias planted from seed will also produce tubers their very first year too. 

If you want to give it a try or you’re looking for seeds, I collected tons of seeds from this years field & we will be offering our dahlia seeds for sale at our upcoming seed sale towards the end of January.

When I first started flower farming teaching was honestly the furthest thing from my mind. In the early days of my journey I was so busy soaking up every bit of knowledge that I could get my hands on that sharing my love of flowers to me back then meant creating beautiful bouquets to share with my community. 
As my journey went on though, I started getting a lot of questions from gardeners & growers about my sweet peas and this is where the idea for my Sweet Pea School Workshop was born. I never imagined that I would love teaching as much as I do. The energy & excitement that I get from this class is something that I have a hard time putting into words. It feeds my soul in a way that I never could’ve dreamed of. Sharing my love of sweet peas with you has grown & blossomed into so much more than the flowers. It’s allowed me to share these amazing blooms with so many of you from all over the world. Every time I teach this class my soul is renewed, refreshed & it becomes even clearer to me that this is what I’m supposed to do. After all those years of working in IT I like to think that the flowers found me. This is where I’m supposed to be, growing sweet peas! 

If you attended this weekend’s class, thank you so much for joining me. I hope you had fun, were inspired & received a ton of information to be successful with your sweet peas this season. For those of you that are interested in attending Sweet Pea School, I just added another class on 1/20. Tickets are now available on our website & I would love to have you join me. Let’s make this your year for great sweet peas!
